{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionLarge language models (LLM), including the GPT series, have emerged as a promising tool to revolutionize many domains in medicine [1][2].",
    "LLMs distinguished themselves from traditional natural language processing models by their ability to generate responses that align with users' expectations [3], without requiring dedicated fine-tuning on specialized tasks [4].",
    "Medical evidence summarization is one of these areas where GPT is promising to improve the traditional process of extracting information from the vast amount of medical research papers [5][6][7].Medical literature screening is one of the major application domains of automatic medical information summarization and extraction.",
    "Before the advent of ChatGPT, one prominent approach to streamlining the screening process involved recommending articles based on relevance, thereby facilitating the prioritization of manual screening or providing suggestions for inclusion and exclusion [8].",
    "Numerous software tools have been developed to realize these functions, such as Rayyan [9], RobotReviewer [10], and SWIFT-Review [11]."
  ],
